  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Largest Rectangle in Histogram\n\nGiven bar heights in a histogram, return the area of the largest rectangle that can be formed by adjacent bars.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: heights = [2, 1, 5, 6, 2, 3]\nOutput: 10\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: heights = [2, 4]\nOutput: 4\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: heights = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]\nOutput: 9\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Input sizes follow the original interview-style constraints.\n- Return values must match the described behavior.",
  "editorial": "Use a stack to keep unresolved items. When a new token, bar, or value resolves earlier items, pop them and update the answer.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def largestRectangleArea(self, heights):\n        stack = []\n        best = 0\n        for i, height in enumerate(heights + [0]):\n            while stack and height < heights[stack[-1]]:\n                h = heights[stack.pop()]\n                left = stack[-1] if stack else -1\n                best = max(best, h * (i - left - 1))\n            stack.append(i)\n        return best\n```",
  "hints": [
    "A stack is useful when the most recent unresolved item should be handled first.",
    "Keep extra state on the stack when constant-time queries are needed."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def largestRectangleArea(self, heights):\n        pass\n"
  },
